  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent and report money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Alerting authorities to potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n\n4. Record-keeping regulations\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n- Preserving customer identification documents\n- Retaining financial transaction documentation\n\n5. Legal penalties\n- Potential fines for non-compliance\n- Criminal prosecution for willful violations\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced through laws like the Bank Secrecy Act and regulations from agencies such as FinCEN in the United States.\n\nFinancial institutions must actively work to detect, prevent, and report potential money laundering activities to maintain legal compliance and prevent financial crimes.",
